<subSubSection id="458765270844FFBA01D5FF5AE775DBBE" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="0D2236AC0844FFBA01D5FF5AE7E5D946" blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis id="3FE9EABE0844FFBA01D5FF5AE76CD8F5" bold="true" box="[197,311,151,177]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">Remarks</emphasis>
. All specimens cited above were collected by pitfall trap, with the exception of a male (
<collectionCode id="6B8CAE690844FFBA044CFF55E3C0D8F6" box="[1372,1435,152,178]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/23qr-v2gj" name="Instituto Biologico de Sao Paulo" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">IBSP</collectionCode>
<number id="BB55248B0844FFBA0187FF0DE6B9D89E" box="[151,226,192,218]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="60425.0">60425</number>
) collected with winkler extractor. This confirms the suggestion by 
<bibRefCitation id="690C4B5D0844FFBA02E3FF0DE2FFD89E" author="Santos" box="[1011,1188,192,218]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refString="Santos, A. J. (2007 a) A revision of the Neotropical nursery-web spider genus Architis (Araneae: Pisauridae). Zootaxa, 1578, 1 - 40." type="journal article" year="2007" yearSuffix="a">
Santos (
<number id="BB55248B0844FFBA0541FF0DE2D4D89E" box="[1105,1167,192,218]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="2007.0">2007</number>
a)
</bibRefCitation>
that this is an active, ground-dwelling species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0D2236AC0844FFBA01D6FEDDE34DDAFE" blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
Female specimens from above locality have a marked variation in the morphology of the epigynum. Instead of lateral lobes that project posteriorly and over the median field, as observed in all specimens examined earlier (
<bibRefCitation id="690C4B5D0844FFBA003BFEADE465D93E" author="Santos" box="[299,574,352,378]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refString="Santos, A. J. (2007 a) A revision of the Neotropical nursery-web spider genus Architis (Araneae: Pisauridae). Zootaxa, 1578, 1 - 40." type="journal article" year="2007" yearSuffix="a">
Santos 
<number id="BB55248B0844FFBA0092FEADE79BD93E" box="[386,448,352,378]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="2007.0">2007</number>
a; fig. 
<number id="BB55248B0844FFBA0318FEADE47DD93E" box="[520,550,352,378]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="19.0">19</number>
D
</bibRefCitation>
), these spiders have the lateral lobes projected ventrally and with a markedly hyaline ventral face leaving the median field completely exposed (
<figureCitation id="95A62A290844FFBA02C7FE45E245D9E6" box="[983,1054,392,418]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 10" captionStartId="5.[151,269,1714,1738]" captionTargetBox="[186,1421,240,1675]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,194,1690]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 10. Architis spp. 7 – 8, Architis neblina Santos &amp; Nogueira sp. nov. (paratype IBSP 91474): 7, female epigynum, ventral view; 8, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. 9 – 10, Architis capricorna Carico (IBSP 94871): 9, female epigynum, ventral view; 10, male pedipalpus, ventral-retrolateral view. The arrow points to a hyaline area at the retrolateral-posterior border of the cymbial alveolus. Abbreviations: C, conductor; CD, copulatory ducts; dRTA, dorsal branch of retrolateral tibial apophysis; DTP, distal tegular projection; FD, fertilisation ducts; HS, head of spermathecae; LL, lateral lobes of epigynum; MA, median apophysis; MF, median field of epigynum; RP, retrolateral projection of VTA; SC, sclerotised case of CD; SK, spermathecal knob; SS, stalk of spermathecae; ST, subtegulum; vRTA, ventral branch of retrolateral tibial apophysis; VTA, ventral tibial apophysis. Scale bars: 7 – 9, 0.1 mm; 10, 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/182891/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
Fig. 
<number id="BB55248B0844FFBA051DFE45E245D9E6" box="[1037,1054,392,418]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). However, the internal genitalia and male pedipalpus are virtually undistinguishable from those of specimens from other localities (but see comments on male genitalia below), suggesting this species has a dimorphic epigynum. Genitalic dimorphism or polymorphism has been observed in other spiders species such as the oxyopid 
<taxonomicName id="CA9D4D2F0844FFBA057BFDCDE685DA06" authority="Hentz, 1832" authorityName="Hentz" authorityYear="1832" class="Arachnida" family="Oxyopidae" genus="Peucetia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viridans">
<emphasis id="3FE9EABE0844FFBA057BFDCDE360DA5D" box="[1131,1339,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">Peucetia viridans</emphasis>
(Hentz, 
<number id="BB55248B0844FFBA0187FDE5E68DDA06" box="[151,214,552,578]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="1832.0">1832</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
, the salticid 
<taxonomicName id="CA9D4D2F0844FFBA0062FDE5E542DA06" authority="Crane 1945" authorityName="Crane" authorityYear="1945" box="[370,793,552,578]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Bryantella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="smaragdus">
<emphasis id="3FE9EABE0844FFBA0062FDE5E42DDA05" box="[370,630,552,577]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">Bryantella smaragdus</emphasis>
(Crane 
<number id="BB55248B0844FFBA03C5FDE5E54ADA06" box="[725,785,552,578]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="1945.0">1945</number>
