). It is not clear whether this is a rare phenomenon in spiders or if it is common but usually undected due to the preferential use of genitalic organs to delimit spi- der species and the fact that most species are based on few specimens (
<bibRefCitation id="690C4B5D0844FFBA02C5FD6DE236DAFE" author="Jocque" box="[981,1133,672,698]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refString="Jocque, R. (2002) Genitalic polymorphism - a challenge for taxonomy. Journal of Arachnology, 30, 298 - 306." type="journal article" year="2002">
